data-triple-N3.o: "The Talmud is a central text of Rabbinic Judaism, considered second to the Torah. It is also traditionally referred to as Shas (), a Hebrew abbreviation of shisha sedarim, the "six orders" of the Oral Law of Judaism. The Talmud has two components: the Mishnah, the first written compendium of Judaism's Oral Law, and the Gemara (c. 500 CE), an elucidation of the Mishnah and related Tannaitic writings that often ventures onto other subjects and expounds broadly on the Hebrew Bible."@en
